<subSubSection id="C32691B034752B6E30A6FE4CFA0F4756" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B83C23B34752B6E30A6FE4CFA0F4756" blockId="30.[151,1437,258,1975]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E30A6FE4CFEB8449F" bold="true" box="[199,314,474,499]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: The new subspecies differs mainly from the nominate subspecies by having larger teeth and teeth intervals, and low number of teeth in stridulatory file of male. Compared to the nominate subspecies, the calling song of the new subspecies is easily distinguished by a smaller number impulses and typical decrescendo pattern.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32691B034752B6E30A6FDD0FB5A418B" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B83C23B34752B6E30A6FDD0FB7E4613" blockId="30.[151,1437,258,1975]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E30A6FDD0FDAB4733" bold="true" box="[199,553,582,607]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
Description: Male (
<typeStatus id="54877C9934752B6E31CFFDD0FD9E4733" box="[430,540,582,607]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">holotype</typeStatus>
):
</emphasis>
Fastigium as wide as half of the antennal scapus, slightly narrowed frontward and faintly depressed dorsally. Pronotum slightly wider in metazona than prozona, slightly depressed at mesozona laterally; disc of pronotum with a straight frontal margin and faintly concave caudal margin (
<figureCitation id="1307DEBE34752B6E34D0FD18FA9847CB" box="[1201,1306,654,679]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1778,1800]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[151,1436,193,1757]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 22. Dorsal view of pronotum. A–B, P. salmani sp. n. (male); C, P. zonatus datca ssp. n. (male); D, P. variicercis (male); E–F, P. salmani sp. n. (female); G, P. zonatus datca (male); I, P. variicercis (female); J–K, P. varicornis (male and female, not in scale)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242375/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 22G</figureCitation>
). Pronotum slightly raised backward in profile (
<figureCitation id="1307DEBE34752B6E3257FD24FD0F47A7" box="[566,653,690,715]" captionStart="FIGURE 47" captionStartId="53.[151,250,1061,1083]" captionTargetBox="[181,1386,193,1045]" captionTargetId="figure@53.[181,1386,193,1045]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="FIGURE 47. Male and female habitus of Poecilimon zonatus datca ssp. n. from Datça (Muğla).A–B, males; C, female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242425/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 47</figureCitation>
). Tegmina with black longutidunal band, slightly rounded at caudal parts and extends beyond middle of first abdominal tergite. Cu2 of left tegmen roundly projecting at right margin (
<figureCitation id="1307DEBE34752B6E30FEFD6CFE8F467F" box="[159,269,762,787]" captionStart="FIGURE 22" captionStartId="28.[151,250,1778,1800]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1757]" captionTargetId="figure@28.[151,1436,193,1757]" captionTargetPageId="28" captionText="FIGURE 22. Dorsal view of pronotum. A–B, P. salmani sp. n. (male); C, P. zonatus datca ssp. n. (male); D, P. variicercis (male); E–F, P. salmani sp. n. (female); G, P. zonatus datca (male); I, P. variicercis (female); J–K, P. varicornis (male and female, not in scale)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242375/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 22G</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="1307DEBE34752B6E3140FD6DFEF5467F" box="[289,375,763,787]" captionStart="FIGURE 47" captionStartId="53.[151,250,1061,1083]" captionTargetBox="[181,1386,193,1045]" captionTargetId="figure@53.[181,1386,193,1045]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="FIGURE 47. Male and female habitus of Poecilimon zonatus datca ssp. n. from Datça (Muğla).A–B, males; C, female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242425/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">47A–B</figureCitation>
). Hindfemur without spines. Epiproct transversely enlarged. Cerci gradually narrowing distalwards, distal 1/3–1/4 obtusely incurved and slightly tapered apically; there are two rows of denticles distally, preapical row includes 1, subapical row includes 5–6 denticles (
<figureCitation id="1307DEBE34752B6E3300FCD4FC5A4637" box="[865,984,834,859]" captionStart="FIGURE 23" captionStartId="29.[151,250,1927,1949]" captionTargetBox="[311,1275,193,1906]" captionTargetId="figure@29.[311,1275,193,1906]" captionTargetPageId="29" captionText="FIGURE 23. Dorsal view of male cerci.A–H, P.z. zonatus (A, Beydağ, B–C, Bozkır, D–E, Ermenek; F, Esencik, G, Munzur); I–J, P.z. datcassp.n. (Datça)" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242377/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 
<date id="FF82E4FB34752B6E33F4FCD5FC3E4637" box="[917,956,835,859]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" value="1923-01">23I</date>
–J
</figureCitation>
). Subgenital plate wide at proximal part, obtusely narrowed at caudal part, with slightly sinuate and almost straight caudal margin (
<figureCitation id="1307DEBE34752B6E34E6FCF0FB6D4613" box="[1159,1263,870,895]" captionStart="FIGURE 10" captionStartId="17.[151,250,1975,1997]" captionTargetBox="[304,1291,194,1948]" captionTargetId="figure@17.[303,1291,193,1949]" captionTargetPageId="17" captionText="FIGURE 10. Subgenital plate of the males. A, P.tauricola; B–C, P. azizsancar sp. n.; E–G, P. variicercis; H–I, P. salmani sp. n.; J–N, P.z. zonatus; O, P.z. datca ssp. n." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242357/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 10O</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B83C23B34752B6E30A6FC1CFBA74687" blockId="30.[151,1437,258,1975]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E30A6FC1CFE1246CF" bold="true" box="[199,400,906,931]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Stridulatory file:</emphasis>
Male stridulatory file is similar to 
<taxonomicName id="4C3CB9B834752B6E337FFC1AFC2846CF" authorityName="zonatus Bolivar" authorityYear="1899" box="[798,938,908,931]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poecilimon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="zonatus" subSpecies="zonatus">
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E337FFC1AFC2846CF" box="[798,938,908,931]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">P. z. zonatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in general structure, but is distinguished by low number of teeth which are sparsely arranged and relatively larger than in 
<taxonomicName id="4C3CB9B834752B6E347CFC39FB2E46AA" authorityName="zonatus Bolivar" authorityYear="1899" box="[1053,1196,943,966]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poecilimon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="zonatus" subSpecies="zonatus">
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E347CFC39FB2E46AA" box="[1053,1196,943,966]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">P. z. zonatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="1307DEBE34752B6E34DCFC38FAAA46AB" box="[1213,1320,942,967]" captionStart="FIGURE 17" captionStartId="24.[151,250,1386,1408]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,265,1365]" captionTargetId="figure@24.[151,1436,265,1365]" captionTargetPageId="24" captionText="FIGURE 17. Stridulatory file on underside of left tegmen of males. A–C, P. zonatus zonatus (A–B, Erzincan; C, Malatya); D, P. zonatus datca; E–J, P. variicercis (E–G, Erzurum, Şenkaya; H, Erzurum, İnceçay (type locality); I, Erzurum, Uğurlu; J, Erzurum, between Olur–Oltu)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242369/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 17D</figureCitation>
; 
<tableCitation id="C6BEF78034752B6E3557FC38FA0F46AB" box="[1334,1421,942,967]" captionStart="TABLE 3" captionStartId="10.[151,239,1530,1553]" captionText="TABLE 3. Measurement of stridulatory file of the species (no data available for P.varicornis)." pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Table 3</tableCitation>
). Tooth morphology is clearly different from other species of the group (
<figureCitation id="1307DEBE34752B6E33D1FC44FB9A4687" box="[944,1048,978,1003]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="25.[151,250,1927,1949]" captionTargetBox="[321,1261,193,1890]" captionTargetId="figure@25.[321,1263,193,1894]" captionTargetPageId="25" captionText="FIGURE 18. Medial teeth of stridulatory file at higher magnification. A–D, P. zonatus zonatus (A, Erzincan; B, Konya, Taşkent; C, Ermenek; D, Konya, Bozkır); E–F, P. variicercis (E, Erzurum, İnceçay (type locality); F, Erzurum, Şenkaya); G, P. zonatus datca ssp. n.; H, P.salmani sp. n.; I–J, P.vodnensis; K–L, P.salmani." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242371/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 18G</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B83C23B34752B6E30A6FC60FBF04117" blockId="30.[151,1437,258,1975]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E30A6FC60FEE64163" bold="true" box="[199,356,1014,1039]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Bioacoustics:</emphasis>
The calling song is similar to that of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3CB9B834752B6E3366FC61FC134163" box="[775,913,1014,1039]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poecilimon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vodnensis">
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E3366FC61FC134163" box="[775,913,1014,1039]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">P. vodnensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. In the calling songs of the only two males we have studied, the “click”-like syllable are presented in small groups which were repeated in large, irregular intervals (
<figureCitation id="1307DEBE34752B6E3167FBA8FED8413B" box="[262,346,1086,1111]" captionStart="FIGURE 30" captionStartId="39.[151,250,1696,1718]" captionTargetBox="[170,1385,219,1623]" captionTargetId="figure@39.[151,1436,193,1675]" captionTargetPageId="39" captionText="FIGURE 30. Structure of male calling songs of P. salmani sp. n., P.zonatus datca ssp. n. and P.variicercis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242391/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 30</figureCitation>
). The syllables lasted about 9.4 ms and were composed of about 3–4 impulses (
<figureCitation id="1307DEBE34752B6E34AFFBA8FAA3413B" box="[1230,1313,1086,1111]" captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="45.[151,250,1724,1746]" captionTargetBox="[326,1253,207,1683]" captionTargetId="figure@45.[302,1284,193,1702]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="FIGURE 37. The oscillograms and spectral view of the male calling songs of P. zonatus datca and P.vodnensis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242405/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
). The peak frequency of the song had a maximum at about 28 kHz (see for details 
<tableCitation id="C6BEF78034752B6E33D3FBF4FB844117" box="[946,1030,1122,1147]" captionStart="TABLE 4" captionStartId="11.[151,239,152,175]" captionText="TABLE 4. Descriptive statistics for examined characters of male calling songs (data given as averages, additionally" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Table 4</tableCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="1307DEBE34752B6E3472FBF4FBE44117" box="[1043,1126,1122,1147]" captionStart="FIGURE 37" captionStartId="45.[151,250,1724,1746]" captionTargetBox="[326,1253,207,1683]" captionTargetId="figure@45.[302,1284,193,1702]" captionTargetPageId="45" captionText="FIGURE 37. The oscillograms and spectral view of the male calling songs of P. zonatus datca and P.vodnensis." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242405/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B83C23B34752B6E30A6FB10FB5A418B" blockId="30.[151,1437,258,1975]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E30A6FB10FEA541F3" bold="true" box="[199,295,1158,1183]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Female:</emphasis>
Pronotum laterally wider than in male, metazona slightly wider than prozona, strongly depressed (
<figureCitation id="1307DEBE34752B6E30FEFB3CFE8441AF" box="[159,262,1194,1219]" captionStart="FIGURE 47" captionStartId="53.[151,250,1061,1083]" captionTargetBox="[181,1386,193,1045]" captionTargetId="figure@53.[181,1386,193,1045]" captionTargetPageId="53" captionText="FIGURE 47. Male and female habitus of Poecilimon zonatus datca ssp. n. from Datça (Muğla).A–B, males; C, female." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242425/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 47C</figureCitation>
). Tegmina short, slightly extending beyond posterior margin of the pronotum, fully overlapping dorsally. Subgenital plate triangular (
<figureCitation id="1307DEBE34752B6E31AEFB58FDBA418B" box="[463,568,1230,1255]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1953,1975]" captionTargetBox="[162,1406,1049,1928]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[162,1406,1049,1928]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 12. Subgenital plate, gonangulum and lamella from below. A–B, P. salmani sp. n. (Dalyan); C, P. variicercis (Olur, İnceçay), D, P. zonatus datca ssp. n. (Datça), E–G, P. zonatus zonatus, H, P. tauricola (Bolkar Mts.), I, P. azizsancar sp. n. (Uzundere, Dikyar)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242361/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Fig. 12D</figureCitation>
). Ovipositor, gonangulum and lamella as in 
<figureCitation id="1307DEBE34752B6E3446FB58FB1A418B" box="[1063,1176,1230,1255]" captionStart="FIGURE 12" captionStartId="18.[151,250,1953,1975]" captionTargetBox="[162,1406,1049,1928]" captionTargetId="figure@18.[162,1406,1049,1928]" captionTargetPageId="18" captionText="FIGURE 12. Subgenital plate, gonangulum and lamella from below. A–B, P. salmani sp. n. (Dalyan); C, P. variicercis (Olur, İnceçay), D, P. zonatus datca ssp. n. (Datça), E–G, P. zonatus zonatus, H, P. tauricola (Bolkar Mts.), I, P. azizsancar sp. n. (Uzundere, Dikyar)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242361/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Figs. 12D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="1307DEBE34752B6E34C2FB59FB56418B" box="[1187,1236,1231,1255]" captionStart="FIGURE 28" captionStartId="37.[151,250,1912,1934]" captionTargetBox="[188,1400,733,1891]" captionTargetId="figure@37.[188,1400,733,1891]" captionTargetPageId="37" captionText="FIGURE 28. Ovipositor shapes of PZG. A–D, P. z. zonatus (A, Erzincan; B, Malatya; C, Ermenek; D, Konya); E–F, P. variicercis; G, P.z. datcassp.n.; H, P.salmani, sp. n.." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1242387/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">28G</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32691B034752B6E30A6FB64FB7B42DB" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B83C23B34752B6E30A6FB64FD4C43FA" blockId="30.[151,1437,258,1975]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E30A6FB64FEBF4067" bold="true" box="[199,317,1266,1291]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Remarks:</emphasis>
The nominate species was originally described by Bolivar (1899) from Binboğa Mountains (
<collectingRegion id="49F80CD934752B6E30FFFA80FED84043" box="[158,346,1302,1327]" country="Turkey" name="Kahramanmaras" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Kahramanmaraş</collectingRegion>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F32B82AB34752B6E3108FA80FE3C4043" box="[361,446,1302,1327]" name="Turkey" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Turkey</collectingCountry>
). 
<taxonomicName id="4C3CB9B834752B6E31B5FA81FDE44042" authorityName="zonatus Bolivar" authorityYear="1899" box="[468,614,1303,1326]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poecilimon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="zonatus" subSpecies="zonatus">
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E31B5FA81FDE44042" box="[468,614,1303,1326]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">P. z. zonatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
reveals a fragmented distribution in the North-South direction at high altitudes of the mountains of Anatolian diagonal and relatively high plateaus of northern part of Taurus mountains in the East-West direction. The additional faunistic records of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3CB9B834752B6E3313FAC9FB81401A" authorityName="zonatus Bolivar" authorityYear="1899" box="[882,1027,1375,1398]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poecilimon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="zonatus" subSpecies="zonatus">
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E3313FAC9FB81401A" box="[882,1027,1375,1398]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">P. z. zonatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were documented by Çıplak 
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E3501FAC9FA1E401B" box="[1376,1436,1374,1399]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">et al.</emphasis>
(1996), 
<bibRefCitation id="EFADBFCA34752B6E308EFA14FE2340F7" box="[239,417,1410,1435]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" refId="ref25524" refString="Karabag, T. (1958) The Orthoptera fauna of Turkey. A synonymic and distributional catalogue of Turkish Orthoptera. Ankara Universitesi, Fen Fakultesi Yayinlari, Ankara, 198 pp." type="book">Karabağ (1958)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFADBFCA34752B6E31CCFA14FDEC40F7" box="[429,622,1410,1435]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" refId="ref26123" refString="Mol, A., Taylan, M. S., Demir, E. &amp; Sirin, D. (2016) Contribution to the knowledge of Ensifera (Insecta: Orthoptera) fauna of Turkey. Journal of the Entomological Research Society, 18, 75 - 98." type="journal article">
Mol 
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E3182FA12FD9940F7" box="[483,539,1410,1435]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">et al.</emphasis>
(2016)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFADBFCA34752B6E321BFA15FCA740F7" box="[634,805,1411,1435]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" refId="ref26405" refString="Ramme, W. (1931) Beitrage zur Kenntnis der palaearktischen Orthopterenfauna (Tettig. et Acrid.). Mitteilungen aus dem Zoologischen Museum in Berlin, 17, 165 - 200." type="journal article">Ramme (1931)</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFADBFCA34752B6E3351FA14FB9D40F7" box="[816,1055,1410,1435]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" refId="ref26943" refString="Sevgili, H., Demirsoy, A. &amp; Durmus, Y. (2012 b) Orthoptera fauna of Kemaliye (Erzincan). Hacettepe Journal of Biology and Chemistry, Special Issue, 317 - 335." type="book chapter">
Sevgili 
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E33E7FA12FC3C40F7" box="[902,958,1410,1435]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">et al.</emphasis>
(2012b)
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation id="EFADBFCA34752B6E344AFA15FB5040F7" box="[1067,1234,1411,1435]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" refId="ref27258" refString="Uvarov, B. P. (1917) Orthoptera of Caucasia and adjacent countries. II. Diagnosis of new species and varieties from the collection of the Caucasian museum. Bulletin Museum Caucase, 11, 281 - 298." type="journal article">Uvarov (1917)</bibRefCitation>
, and 
<bibRefCitation id="EFADBFCA34752B6E356CFA14FA1A40F7" box="[1293,1432,1410,1435]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" refId="ref27416" refString="Unal, M. (2010) Phaneropterinae (Orthoptera: Tettigoniidae) from Turkey and the Middle East II. Transactions of the American Entomological Society, 136, 125 - 183. https: // doi. org / 10.3157 / 061.136.0203" type="journal article">Ünal (2010)</bibRefCitation>
. 
<bibRefCitation id="EFADBFCA34752B6E30F6FA31FEC040D3" box="[151,322,1446,1471]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" refId="ref26474" refString="Ramme, W. (1951) Zur Systematik, Faunistik und Biologie der Orthopteren von Sudost Europa und Vorderasien. Mitteilungen aus dem Zoologischen Museum, Berlin, 27, 1 - 432, pls. 1 - 39." type="journal article">Ramme (1951)</bibRefCitation>
identified the specimens collected by Dr. O. Schwarz from the Sandras mountain (
<collectingRegion id="49F80CD934752B6E3569FA30FAD640D3" box="[1288,1364,1446,1471]" country="Turkey" name="Mugla" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Muğla</collectingRegion>
) as 
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E35E6FA31FF76408F" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<taxonomicName id="4C3CB9B834752B6E35E6FA31FF72408F" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poecilimon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zonatus">P. zonatus</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
In this research, the samples studied by Ramme were not studied. However, it should be noted that this small population from the Datça Peninsula near the seashore and the populations outside the 
<taxonomicName id="4C3CB9B834752B6E34C6FA79FA99436B" authorityName="Sevgili &amp; Şirin &amp; Heller &amp; Lemonnier-Darcemont" authorityYear="2018" box="[1191,1307,1518,1543]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poecilimon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="salmani">
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E34C6FA79FA99436B" box="[1191,1307,1518,1543]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">P. salmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that spread around the 
<collectingRegion id="49F80CD934752B6E317BF984FE4C4347" box="[282,462,1554,1579]" country="Turkey" name="Mugla" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Muğla province</collectingRegion>
may belong to the newly described subspecies. The new subspecies is distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="4C3CB9B834752B6E30B5F9A1FEC54323" authorityName="Sevgili &amp; Şirin &amp; Heller &amp; Lemonnier-Darcemont" authorityYear="2018" box="[212,327,1590,1615]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poecilimon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="salmani">
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E30B5F9A1FEC54323" box="[212,327,1590,1615]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">P. salmani</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which is known to inhabit the areas of Fethiye and Dalyan and is described as a new species in this study by the differences of the shape of the apical part of male cerci, the shape of gonangulum and lamella in female and colour pattern of tergites in both sexes.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B83C23B34752B6E30A6F934FA8743B3" blockId="30.[151,1437,258,1975]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
The syllable pattern of the calling song is quite similar to that of the macrosyllables of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3CB9B834752B6E34CBF932FABF43D7" box="[1194,1341,1700,1723]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poecilimon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variicercis">
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E34CBF932FABF43D7" box="[1194,1341,1700,1723]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">P. variicercis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but the whole song pattern of 
<taxonomicName id="4C3CB9B834752B6E31F0F951FDA043B2" box="[401,546,1735,1758]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poecilimon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="variicercis">
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E31F0F951FDA043B2" box="[401,546,1735,1758]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">P. variicercis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shows significant differences from this species (see 
<figureCitation id="1307DEBE34752B6E3411F950FB7B43B3" box="[1136,1273,1734,1759]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 36" captionStart-1="FIGURE 37" captionStartId-0="44.[151,250,1983,2005]" captionStartId-1="45.[151,250,1724,1746]" captionTargetBox-0="[352,1232,194,1925]" captionTargetBox-1="[326,1253,207,1683]" captionTargetId-0="figure@44.[352,1232,193,1949]" captionTargetId-1="figure@45.[302,1284,193,1702]" captionTargetPageId-0="44" captionTargetPageId-1="45" captionText-0="FIGURE 36. The oscillograms and spectral view of the male calling songs of P. variicercis." captionText-1="FIGURE 37. The oscillograms and spectral view of the male calling songs of P. zonatus datca and P.vodnensis." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/1242403/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/1242405/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Figs. 36–37</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B83C23B34752B6E30A6F97CFC75424B" blockId="30.[151,1437,258,1975]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
The new subspecies was found together with some orthopterans such as 
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E3464F97CFE59424A" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
<taxonomicName id="4C3CB9B834752B6E3464F97CFABE426F" authorityName="in Heller" authorityYear="1988" box="[1029,1340,1770,1795]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poecilimon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sanctipauli" subGenus="Poecilimon">Poecilimon (P.) sanctipauli</taxonomicName>
, P. (H.). hamatus, 
<taxonomicName id="4C3CB9B834752B6E3165F898FE36424B" authorityName="Maran" authorityYear="1953" box="[260,436,1806,1831]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Eupholidoptera" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Eupholidoptera</taxonomicName>
sp.
</emphasis>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C3CB9B834752B6E3270F898FCA3424B" authorityName="Karabag" authorityYear="1953" box="[529,801,1806,1831]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Orchamus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="yersini" subSpecies="davisi">
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E3270F898FCA3424B" box="[529,801,1806,1831]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">Orchamus yersini davisi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<typeStatus id="54877C9934752B6E3307F899FC14424B" box="[870,918,1807,1831]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">type</typeStatus>
locality.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B83C23B34752B6E30A6F8A4FB7B42DB" blockId="30.[151,1437,258,1975]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">
This species has not been assessed for the 
<collectionCode id="ED2D5AFE34752B6E32C3F8A5FD644227" box="[674,742,1843,1867]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">IUCN</collectionCode>
Red List (2017–3). The distribution of the 
<taxonomicName id="4C3CB9B834752B6E34ADF8A2FA004227" authorityName="Sevgili &amp; Şirin &amp; Heller &amp; Lemonnier-Darcemont" authorityYear="2018" box="[1228,1410,1842,1867]" class="Insecta" family="Tettigoniidae" genus="Poecilimon" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Orthoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="zonatus" subSpecies="datca">
<emphasis id="B9481E2934752B6E34ADF8A2FA004227" box="[1228,1410,1842,1867]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">P. zonatus datca</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is highly restricted and its habitats are under the threat by anthropogenic effects, such as stubble fire, over-use of pesticides in agriculture, touristic activities and grazing. For these reasons, the species should be considered with a Critically Endangered (B1ab(i, iii)) status on the basis of the extent of occurrence criteries of 
<collectionCode id="ED2D5AFE34752B6E34CFF809FB7442DB" box="[1198,1270,1951,1975]" pageId="30" pageNumber="31">IUCN</collectionCode>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
